  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained funds appear legitimate by concealing their true origin. This practice is illegal because it facilitates criminal activities, undermines the integrity of financial systems, and violates laws designed to prevent and combat financial crimes.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited under laws such as the Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China (\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u53cd\u6d17\u94b1\u6cd5), which was enacted to combat such activities and maintain the stability of the financial system. Violators face severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences.\n\nThe Chinese government actively enforces anti-money laundering regulations through collaboration with domestic and international agencies to ensure compliance and deter criminal activity.",
